"{\n  \"text\": \"Hello everybody, my name is Scotty. I'm the owner of Scotty's Fermented Foods. Fermented Foods have long been associated with gut health, and this is actually very true in my experience. I've seen my own health improve, but I've seen so many other people who had gut conditions who have done much to alleviate their symptoms and much to alleviate their conditions. And one of these people is a very unique young man who I had the pleasure of meeting uh with his mother at um when I first started this business uh about six years ago, and he was four or five, five or six, something of that nature. And um he is a young boy with autism, he is nonverbal, and when I first saw him, he was in pretty bad shape. He um looked to have a lot of pain. He had a very wild eye. He was uh full of what they call stemming, which is um a form of self-stimulation, or that's what the word is, but this was much more indicative of pain, and it was a very sad condition. And his mother was anxious to try to help this. She had done a lot already, and she was uh getting into fermented foods and was looking for living raw fermented foods, which is what I do. Um the turnaround of this young man was just remarkable. And uh I I I want to lead in with that, but this is their story, and I had a unique opportunity to interview um the uh parents of this young man uh and tell their story, uh, let them tell their story. It's simply phenomenal. And anyway, I just wanted to lead in with that just to tell you that you know, when I first ran across uh this family, uh this was a very severe condition. Um of course, he is still a young man with autism, he is still non-verbal, but his turnaround and his progress has been absolutely remarkable. And I've viewed it firsthand over the past six years. And uh so anyway, without a further ado, this is their story. What were the first indications that your son um might have autism? What was the first signs? How old was he? We didn't ex he was our first child. So we being the first child, things that we saw we thought were normal. Um we really didn't accept the things that were going on. I mean, he never slept when he was firstborn. I mean, he was he he was always crying and stuff, but he still was making making some milestones in um saying words, um recognizing us. Um things started changing where he started losing his vocabulary around age one. Age one, yeah, twelve months. I think by 14 months we totally lost him. We were one of the stories of he looked out the window and did not see us as mommy and daddy. He was completely gone. Right, right. And so he was developing language functions, he was developing social functions, and then regressed at a certain point. Yeah, it was just like almost an instant thing in a way. Right, yeah, yeah. Look looking back, it was almost from day one. We didn't know it, we didn't know the signs. He would never sleep laying down. No, I couldn't change his type for it. And what was happening, yeah. He he would always flip over, he wanted to sleep in the car seat. Uh, if we put him down to sleep, he would scream. What I came to find out many, many, many years later was it was acid reflux. And we didn't know that. We had no idea. Yeah. And you know, of course, when I learned that, it just part. He had an uh an overload of yeast too. I didn't realize that I had an overload of yeast, and I breastfed all the way up until 14 months. So the yeast in my body was going into him. So on top of acid reflux, he was getting an overload of yeast into his gut system. What we've learned is whatever gut the parent has, the mother has, you pass it on to the child. Yes. Even though I didn't drink, I didn't smoke, I didn't do drugs, my gut was still unhealthy because I had allergies really bad. Um, I had um mercury in my mouth from fillings, and whatever you have goes into the child. General American diet. Yeah, or and the general American conditions, not just our diet, we're waging war against bacteria, and a lot of us are facing gut disorders through not really any fault of our own. You know, this isn't uh I was doing this horrible, you know, living this horrible lifestyle. A lot of times it's just the way things go down that gut disorders are occurring. I mean, environmental toxins and stuff here. And yeah, that's that's a real thing that like the um our world is much more toxic than it was just 60, 70 years ago. There's been a lot of things that are cumulative, you know, uh effects on term in terms of toxicity, and in the meantime our body is less and less able to fight these uh toxins, so it's they combine and pretty soon we're all sick. Yeah. Um before you began um following a gut healthy diet or gut healthy regimen in terms of the diet with your son, what was his general behavior? What was what describe to us um what he was like? Very active, never could sit still, um lost language. Um he started walking on his tippy toes. Um he seemed to be in pain. His stomach gassy. He had a belly lip, yeah. It was gassy here and had a belly because he was had had pain in here. Same same reason for walking on that tippy toes. Was there a lot of stimulation? Self stimulation, it was self-standing. He had to jump a lot. He had to jump on. There was a little bit of yeah, the a little bit of moving and stuff that seemed a little odd. But nothing too but I mean it was just he he never slept. That was the biggest thing. This child never slept. Yeah, he never slept. Um he when he got older, he was always upset when and then when he got older before we started the diet, he got extremely aggressive. There was a few times when he was younger where he would just kind of sit there and stare out the window, and he was just, you know, when we would go to I take him to the playground and he just sit there, and he was either tired or just in pain. There was no eye contact. We could never get eye contact from him. But yeah, then as the years went on before the diet, it he got aggressive. But that also, I think his gut also deteriorated more and more. And he, even though he was eating, it wasn't digesting. Yeah. And he wasn't getting the blood sugar, he wasn't getting the nutrition. His kid can't remember. How much he could eat, he was still starving. Right. And with that drop blood sugar, he was just getting upset. And he was getting violent, um, grabbing, pinching, biting, just anything. I mean, he was just asking. He was begging for help. Yeah, all these all these you're describing it sounds like signs of pain and trauma that he's got to be. But we didn't try to do it. Yes, of course. We didn't know what was going on. We go to the doctor and they're like, oh, that's normal. You know, we say, hey, he's pooping out everything that's he's eating. The doctor's like, oh, well, he's as long as you know it's going through the city. Yeah, he's still getting nutrition. And I'm just sitting here thinking this doesn't sound right. Well, we go back um uh back to when he was about three years old, you know, when we we kind of started accepting that there was something wrong. Um they told us to the recommendation was to go a gluten-free, casein-free, soy-free diet. Right, restriction diet. Restrictions. So we went into that and we started seeing some results from that. But it's so hard. And at that time you didn't have all the options you have in the grocery store. I mean, I walked in the store and I would just start calling because I'm like, what am I supposed to feed my kid? You know, and I didn't realize that I needed to shop outside the perimeters of the grocery store, and now inside the perimeter of the grocery store where all the pre-made stuff was. And um, but I also didn't realize that the stuff that we have now that are gluten-free, casein-free, soy-free, has a lot of sugar in it. It's like the first ingredient. And that's not feeding the good bacteria in your gut. Yeah. So it's dead food. Yes, it's dead food. And then this is something that a lot of people are are learning that processed foods by definition are dead foods, and there's maybe some nutritional value, but in terms of how your system is taking them on, it's inert matter. There's there's not a healthy response because there's not a bacterial response to them. But um, yeah, so I I can that whole thing about the center of the grocery store being the processed areas, the dead areas, and having to go around the sections that around the outsides, even those are oftentimes dead foods. Very true. The yogurts. Yeah, the yogurts are all sorts of yogurt that are all about bacteria. This is not and nothing about living. Yeah. I I can tell the difference, yeah. Yeah.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hello everybody, my name is Scotty.\",\n      \"start\": 0.64,\n      \"end\": 2.64,\n      \"duration\": 2.0,\n      \"confidence\": 0.985,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" H\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.996\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ello\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.2,\n          \"duration\": 0.24,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 1.28,\n          \"end\": 1.44,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 1.44,\n          \"end\": 1.52,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 1.52,\n          \"end\": 1.68,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \",\",\n          \"start\": 1.68,\n          \"end\": 1.76,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.936\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" my\",\n          \"start\": 1.76,\n          \"end\": 1.84,\n